segments.text: Justice Serenello interview, November 11, 1985.
All right, Lance, will you donate this to Texas A&M University?
Is that OK?
Yes.
Thank you.
Let me check.
But I talked to Stephanie.
I listened to her tape a couple of times, and I looked at her question, and so I want to try to take off what she talked about.
She talked about some things that were pretty broad, and I want to try to get into detail on a couple of things.
Sure.
Plus ask some other questions.
First off, just for general information, when and where were you born?
I was born August 4th, 1948 in Brooklyn, New York.
I understand you started school at City College in New York in 67.
Yes.
And you came to Southwest in the fall of 69.
That's true.
And then in the fall of 70, you went back to City College in New York.
And you finished up there in June of 72.
Yes.
And when did you attend law school and where?
I attended law school at the University of Texas at Austin from September of 73 until May of 76.
OK.
In the interview with Stephanie, you called the Vietnam War a great disaster for the American youth.
When did your feelings against the war begin, and when did they intensify?
The feelings against the war began, I would say, in 64, 65, when I was still in high school.
And the reason I saw the war as not having any purpose
It seemed like something that we were caught up in, but yet we're not able to advance any cause or help anyone, that we were really advancing our own interests in Southeast Asia.

And I think as time went on, it became more apparent it was not the kind of war, a conventional war, that Americans were used to fighting, where we would go in and win in a few months or a year or so, and that we were becoming hopelessly mired in something that
basically offered no expectation of a victory or something that was satisfying from the point of view of the American government.
Well, apparently that's what made you speak out against the war.
You mentioned in the other interview that you were taught to question in high school.
Do you think that was part of it?
Also, I take it your parents, from what I understand in the interview,
pretty much conform to the authority.
Right.
They were basically very authoritarian minded.
They never thought of questioning authority or they basically believed in following whatever the government policies were.
And I think in high school, I learned more about just questioning, not accepting, and beginning to ask, why are we in this war?
What have we got to gain?
What is our purpose?
And the more you ask those questions, I think it became apparent
that we really didn't have a solid purpose in being there, and that the government kept expanding our involvement.
And of course, I began to be of draft age and began to be thinking as well from my own standpoint.
I think a lot of other people my age were thinking, well, we might go over there and get killed.
And what are we doing it for?
And many of us thought, this is not right.
There wasn't any purpose.
At that point, I remembered my history courses about World War II and thought about what American youth were like in the early 40s.

And to me, there seemed to be a distinct difference between then fighting someone who had the potential of threatening our freedom as opposed to what had we to fear from the government of South Vietnam or North Vietnam?
What had the Americans had to fear?
Surely, they were not going to get in the boats
come across to the West Coast or get in planes.
I mean, and things like that, which at this point seem rather simple or rather straightforward.
Yet at that time, most people were just unquestioned support of Vietnam or the government.
What kind of an upbringing did you have?
Did your parents punish you in any way when you didn't go by what they said and you questioned?
Yeah, punishment was usually corporal by spanking or slapping or taking away privileges or things like that.
I grew up in a tenement in Brooklyn in the early 50s.
So, I mean, we were basically, by most standards, poor.
And there wasn't a whole lot they could take away, but basically time to spend on the street playing.
What is your religion?
I'm Catholic.
You are Catholic.
Right.
Also, from the high school, was it because of your teachers, or was it because of your peers where you were cross-questioned?
I think it was a combination of teachers and peers.
The high school I went to required an entrance exam in New York City.
It was one of three high schools that you had to take an entrance exam to get into.
And generally, it was nearly everyone there went on to college, and it was different from the neighborhood high schools.
Was it a private school?
No, it was a public school.
Public?
Mm-hmm.
But that was the only requirement
Was it close to your home?
No, it was not.
It was about an hour subway ride from my home.
The reason I went there was because it was a very good high school.

Do you think some of the students that protested the war, especially say in 69 when you were leading a lot of them, do you think they did it because it was bashing, they were just following the crowd, pick up a chick, you know, I'm protesting, we'll get some drugs, or do you think some of them
sincerely had reservations about the war and wanted to do something about it?
I think it's a combination.
I think there were certainly some people who were in it because it was a fad or it was the cheap thing to do at that time.
But I think most people had genuine reservations about the war and what was happening.
And people at that point in 69 knew of, had friends who had either died in Vietnam or injured in Vietnam,
And in fact, one of the people that I was kicked out of school with had been Vietnam.
And at that point in 69, you had a lot of Vietnam veterans speaking out against the war.
And on the campus of Southwest, there were a number of veterans who spoke out against it.
And I think it was more than just because it was fashionable, although at this point in 69, demonstrations had become somewhat fashionable.
However, in Southwest Texas State, they were not.
The demonstration that we had in October of 69 was the first anti-war demonstration they ever had in that town or that county.
So on the 15th in conjunction with Vietnam War?
That's right.
And then the second one was in November when we were suspended.
I'll get more into that.
You mentioned in the other interview also that maybe 10% of the students at any one time
participated in demonstrations.
And so looking back, do you think that was a good percentage, a good turnout?
Or do you think it could have done better?
We thought it was a good turnout then, because initially there was very little support.
And in the October moratorium, there was a fair number of students more than we had expected.
And in November, it had grown.
And we thought that the turnout was improving.
you'd like to have had 100%.
You don't expect that.
And at that point, given what was going on in many campuses of the size and temperament of San Marcos, I thought that was a good turnout.
And we certainly, in October, the auditorium that we had for our speakers was completely overflowing with people.
In fact, there were speakers outside for the people who were sitting outside.
Good job.
You said you were aware of your involvement, your interest began in 64, 65.
Was it just from watching television?

Were you aware of specific events, such as, well, a couple instances that I noticed doing research that were very important, such as the spring mobilization and the war in April of 67, the Rolling Thunder in 68, which started in 64 but lasted until 68, which was just
constant bombing of North Vietnam by the American troops.
Were there particular instances that you could isolate on?
Well, I would say that a number of our professors in high school or teachers encouraged us to think about the war, about what was going on.
And I can't pinpoint any one thing, but I think it was certainly some of the speakers that we had in high school also encouraged us to think about the war.
Our valedictory speech in high school, the valedictorian basically gave an anti-war speech.
And it just seemed that it was very frequent in conversation, not just on television, because television at that time, in 64, 65, was basically pro-administration.
I mean, there was some questioning of it, and there was not a lot of any more sentiment, although there was a fair amount growing in New York and some of the major eastern cities.
But it was still...
considered still very anti-government, un-American, to have been against the war at that time.
How involved were you in your first two years at City College?
I was involved in some demonstrations and some planning of demonstrations with the committees up there and the anti-war groups up there.
But it was basically a loose amalgam of organizations and activities.
It was not well organized.
Reading the article, it said that you liked the Kentucky Hill Country and such.
Is that all that enticed you to transfer down to Santa Barbara?
That's right.
One of my hobbies at that time was skydiving.
It still is.
And I took a couple of weeks in summer in college and just went around the country skydiving.
And St. Marcus had a nice gym center.
I thought the Hill Country was pretty, and I decided to.
I wanted to go just to a different kind of school and pick Southwest Texas State.
And Texas at that time was inexpensive for out-of-state students, and that was another factor.
Going down there then and starting your junior year, did you expect or did you anticipate what you were going to get involved in?
No, I did not expect that I would get.
I thought I would be involved in some anti-war activities.
I assumed that there would be some kind of existing ongoing organization on campus and that I would participate.
But when I got there, I found out that there really wasn't any such an entity.
And therefore, I proceeded to try and work with some other people to try and get some anti-war activity going, at least some mobilization and some effort to express
our feelings against the war.
And this is when you met in the coffee house and started the ad hoc committee?
That's right.
Was that solely your responsibility?
Did you dream that up, or did you run into these other eight individuals?
Was it all of your own meaning?
I think it was a matter of just, I wouldn't say it was solely my idea.
It was just something that we more or less decided to do and form to get some organized activity against the war on campus.
These other eight, were they all gentlemen?
Were they all men?
No.
See, there were three women and seven males.
And actually, several of them were not involved in the anti-war activities really until that demonstration in November.
And of course, there were a lot of people at the demonstration site.
And once the university came and roped off the area and said, you've got three minutes to vacate,
then many people left.
And it was just the 10 of us that stayed.
I don't know if you were aware of that.
Essentially, the way it happened is that we had negotiated with the administration for a space on the campus to have a demonstration.
And at that point, the administration said, no, we're not going to let you have anything outside except in what was called at that time the free speech area, which was an area
not centrally located on campus, and you could only demonstrate for one hour.
We had the exact same thing.
Do you?
Okay.
Well, we consulted with some attorneys in Austin through the American Civil Liberties Union.

They advised us that, in their opinion, they didn't think that was constitutional, that we had a right to express ourselves, you know, as long as we were not obstructing traffic and not disturbing classes.
And so we then proceeded to hold the demonstration on a grassy area and not make any noise.
The administration came down, roped off the area, and said, you've got three minutes to leave or you'll be suspended.
And 10 of us stayed.
And then they suspended us.
I mean, there were TV cameras there.
It was on the news that night.
It was apparently.
So immediately you were suspended.
And when was it that the circuit judge?
What happened was we were suspended on November 9, or whenever it happened, November.
Was that November?
Was it the 15th?
Was it the second moratorium?
It was the second moratorium, whatever that was.
Maybe it was the 15th.
In November, and then we were reinstated about three weeks later by the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals.
Judge Roberts in Austin denied our request for reinstatement.
The Fifth Circuit granted our request, and therefore we were allowed to continue in school until the end of the school year.
However,
We were not granted any credit.
The university would not give us credit until, you know, the issue was finally resolved on the merits.
And we lost on the merits.
To the Supreme Court in 72.
What did you do those three weeks that you were suspended?
Were you still...
I was still involved in some anti-war activities or just mobilizing, you know.
There were some other demonstrations.
We had demonstrations about
people trying to convince the administration to put us back in school.
In fact, the night we got suspended, there were probably as many as 3,000 students that attended the demonstration.
And many students, even those who were not against the war, just felt like that was just excessive.
It was just unfair to throw us out of school for what we did.
I take it when you were suspended, and then when you were reinstated into school, it was about finals time, then, wasn't it?
Mm-hmm.
Did you come back in the spring semester?
Yes, I did.
But all this time, even though the spring semester, all the time you were taking classes, those credits, too, were questionable.
Right.
Because the suspension from the university was for one academic year.
Okay.
And so, therefore, the university allowed us to attend school.
It would not produce any credits.
And so my transcript just reads one paragraph from the Southwest Texas statement.
It cites the case and says that all credits denied.
And then after that, that's when we went back to Citadel.
What kind of a communication network did you have going to reach your supporters?
It was a combination of telephones.
We had a telephone bank of people.
We also had one person in each dorm that was responsible for motivating or getting people out or letting people know what was happening.
We had people in various parts of the student community that lived in the town that would basically be assigned to different areas.
And we then used notices that we would put around.
Such as flyers?
Flyers, right.
Where did you get the funding for things like that?
The owner of one of the bookstores, Bob Barton, was a legislator up until two years ago.
He had been a newspaperman in San Marcos.
He supported us with funding, donated money, and donated some printing press materials.
And you also had a couple underground papers.
That's right.
We had the Purgatory Creek Press.
And there was the Weather Report.
Weather Report, that was it.
Your group and the organizers, were they in charge of that, or just someone else?
The Weather Report was done by someone else, and the Purgatory Creek Press was also done by some other people.
In fact, a journalism student who'd been removed off the newspaper was in charge of
the Purgatory Creek Press.
And he's now, or was at one time, a city councilman in St. Lawrence.
And those publications, what would be printed in those?
They were mainly articles about the warm Vietnam or about issues on the campus regarding students or women.
Women's rights at that point was sort of an emerging issue.
I wish I
I'm sure I've got copies of them somewhere, they're just difficult to locate.
But they were pretty, in terms of the reporting in the articles, they were not unbiased by any means.
They were quite slanted.
And there was a lot of hype and a lot of rhetoric.
Did you all ever read E.T.
's Frag?
Yeah.
And did you have any communication going with Moe or SNC?
We did, and we got some of the national and regional flyers and brochures that were printed and put out.
How would you obtain that information?
Did you contact them and they'd mail it to you?
We were in contact with the Austin SMC office and then the Washington office, but mainly through the Austin office.
And with your group, was there one person who was more or less the president, the leader?
Not really, although, I mean, I didn't,
you know, informally, you know, attributed to being the leader.
But I think we all, you know, we all had, we were all quite strong individuals.
And it wasn't the kind of group where nine of you followed one person and we all had our own ideas.
You know, and it was somewhat diverse.
We weren't monolithic in terms of our viewpoint or outlook by any means.
And I would say that, you know, we were a,
a loosely banded together group of people, and there wasn't any one particular leader.
Although, again, I've been attributed to that, to being the leader, or been referred to as that, but I think everyone had different ideas, and everyone had some important ideas.
When did, going back to the Ad Hoc Committee, when exactly did that start?
Was it right at the beginning of the...
It was right at the beginning.
I'd say about
Oh, the first week of September we removed it.
And were your main efforts in to get ready for the first moratorium?
Because the first moratorium was coming about, and the idea was to have some sort of campus-wide activity.
And at first the administration was very reluctant, but they agreed to do it.
And it was only after they got all this negative response from people in the community, alumni, whatever, that they really tried to come down on us on the second one.
What happened with that first one?
What did you do exactly?
We had Senator Schwartz at that time, I believe.
Well, we had some professors speak about the war in Vietnam.
And again, it was the auditorium that we had was just overflowing with people.
That's where you had him?
And that's all it entailed, were speakers at the auditorium, no marches, no sittings?
We had a short march, but it was not very lengthy.
But that was the extent.
And we handed out flyers and brochures, trying to encourage other people to think about the war more.
When this was starting and you were getting involved in 69, were you even up with the
other campuses across the country and what they were doing?
We were only mainly through the newspaper and then through the, we'd occasionally attend some regional meetings in Austin about what was going on.
But that was pretty much the extent of it.
You had the two moratoriums.
Is there any other demonstrations that you're involved in at Southwest during your stay?
There, I believe in February we had
another anti-war activity, which, according to our, you know, basically following the advice of our lawyers, we just strictly followed the administration's guidelines about the demonstration.
We had a demonstration in response to Kent State.
That was the vigil.
The vigil, right.
And then we also had a demonstration regarding a foreign student that the university was apparently trying to punish for his political ideas.
I learned later, we had a march on the administration building to the dean's office.
And I later learned that the dean thought we were going to try and destroy records.
And they hoarded everything, all these safes closed or vaults closed.
It was just amazing.
But we just marched to the dean's office to talk to the dean about what was happening to the students.
So there were never any draft card burnings, sit-ins, anything that was a little more radical than just?
No, nothing.
more radical, nothing where the wall was broken or anything like that.
That did not happen.
And basically, we thought that would not be a good step to take, especially in light of the fact that we were already involved in this litigation over the suspension in November.
I mean, it's quite possible that if nothing had happened in November, that we might have gone further and done more, and there might have been some sit-ins.
I don't know whether there would have been draft card burnings, but there might have been some sit-ins.
or something around that.
But I think there was an attempt, really, to try and stay within the law.
I just thought we had the upper hand that way in trying not to do something that could provoke the administration or give them grounds.
I mean, we were never arrested at the demonstration.
It was strictly a civil matter.
Never any arrests during the protests?
No.
Never any arrests.
It was closely monitored by the police, but we never
Well, what was the administration's reason for asking you to leave?
They said that the demonstration was disrupting the campus.
And here we were being punished because there were lots of people hollering and yelling at us, you know, commies, you know, Yankee agitator, and that sort of thing.
And I assume it probably was disruptive to certain classrooms, but it wasn't us
It was causing the disruption.
We were not saying anything.
We were not blocking any paths.
But that was the administration's reasoning.
In fact, they had several professors testify at the trial that their classrooms were being disrupted by the noise.
Of course, the professors couldn't testify as to who was making the noise because they didn't see it.
But we had testimony about who was making the noise and that nothing was done to stop people who were making the noise
or disperse the crowd that was gathering.
So, I mean, from that standpoint, it's fairly ludicrous to blame us for disrupting.
I mean, we were sitting on a grass knoll, just ten of us.
I mean, yeah, it's absurd at this point, but that's the way the administration viewed it.
And, of course, they had Jack Roberts, who was the district judge that heard the case at that time.
He was an LBJ appointee.
After, you know, one minute,
of the case closing, he rendered a decision against us.
And it was just, pardon me, I mean, you're taking it under your belt.
So you think that his decision was a little far?
Yeah, his decision was made up before he ever heard the avenues, I'm sure.
But, you know, we did not win the Fifth Circuit on the trial of the merits.
And when it went up to the Supreme Court and lost at that point, so sure it was denied.
You know, the way the facts come out in the case, and what I might try to do is get you a copy of the opinion.
It appears that we were not being reasonable in our negotiations with the administration.
So there are some facts that don't come out clearly.
But we were trying to negotiate.
The administration just did not view this as an embarrassment.
It viewed the fact that we, because a lot of the other schools in Texas on the level of Southwest Texas State were not having any demonstrations.
And it was an embarrassment to this administration
their students were protesting and demonstrating.
The view was, can't you, the administrators, stop these people?
Can't you do something to sweep them under the rug?
And so they were very upset.
They were determined to keep us from having a large demonstration like we had in October.
These people that were yelling at you and such, were they people from the community, other students?
There were other students, mainly cowboys, people who just
them raised in Texas with old backgrounds.

Did you ever get into any type of debates with, just verbal debates back and forth and ask them why they were... We had some verbal discussions, although not, that day we had some, but it was mainly some discussion, but it never really got anywhere.
I mean, there was some communication, but a lot of them were fairly hostile.
They saw this as the Communist menace that they mourned about in Sunday school and grammar school.
I just felt like I'd been cast back several years.
It was amazing.
Were they all so primitive?
Yes, they were primitive in terms of their politics and ideology.
They were very dogmatic.
It was just incredible.
Over the course of the year, there was some discussion.
the events of that year, the demonstrations, provoked a lot of class discussion.
And, you know, I think people had a more open view of that.
But that's...
I mean, there was some discussion.
What do you think it is that drives people to protest?
What is it just... Well, it's a combination of things.
I think one is just the sense of
morality of what's right and what's wrong.
That if the government is doing something that's wrong, you as a citizen of that government have an obligation to speak out against it.
I think that's one area.
There's also, you know, where you are directly involved, you know, where you're likely to be drafted.
That's a motivation, particularly in regard to the Vietnam War.
You have a lot of different people.
And there's also
Demonstrations were fashionable.
It was the wartime war.
People meet each other, smoke a little dope.
And that took place, too.
And that was part of it all.
They certainly didn't smoke dope at demonstrations in southwest Texas.
But that was part of it, too.
It's a combination of motives.
But I think that the morality of the war and the draft were probably two main things.
Which one do you think was stronger, the fear of the draft or the disagreement with government policy?
Unfortunately, I think the fear of the draft was probably stronger.
Although I would say many people, the disagreement with government policy was strong, but you had many people who, once the draft was no longer a problem.
Let me rephrase that.
People were not as concerned about what was going on with the government in 72, 73, when I went back to Southwest Texas, when students could then vote.
I mean, they literally could control that city, and yet they chose not to.
It just shocked me.
And students, a lot of them were voting Republican in 72.
It was a disillusion because they just did not have a real concern about what their government was doing.
The draft wasn't as big a problem and they just sort of backed off.
What was the draft age at that time?
It was 18.
And voting and drinking age is 21.
Correct.
In Texas, right.
How did you feel about that when they were asking you to dock your country at 18 and yet you couldn't speak with your vote for...
Well, I thought it was, of course, at that time, I had just turned 21, so I could drink.
But I still thought it was inconsistent.
I thought you shouldn't be in a position where you can be called upon to fight for your country, and you couldn't get a drink.
Yeah, I thought that was outrageous.
But you had a lot of people who were students, I think, who were concerned about the draft.
But there was also this outrage about the war.
Because you also, as I say, by 69,
And people had been seeing it on television, had been watching the weekly death counts.
And people began asking themselves, is this right?
And I think that the demonstrations were a catalyst that people really began to articulate, or at least in their own minds began to formulate that something was not right.
What was it that made you different from everybody else that made you one of the leaders?
Well, I think part of it was a willingness to get something going, to start an activity where there was not an activity there.
I guess it's just my own, I was not willing to accept that there was not going to be some activity or organization to mobilize against the war in southwest Texas State.
I learned to question authority and not just accept things.
And it was an area where there was a need for someone
I mean, if there had been an ongoing campus activity organization, I probably would have participated, but would not have assumed the role that I did.
I think there was a need, and there was a role available, and I wanted to fulfill that role because someone needed to do it.
I understand.
OK. Other such actions, especially reading out
to get involved in the 69, the Tet Offensive, the arrests in Chicago, and things like that.
Did those inspire you even more to voice your opinions to try to get something better?
I think they did.
I think that there was a feeling that the government was lying to us.
The government was really trying to clamp down any kind of expression.
And it made us very angry, because we grew up thinking how wonderful the government was.
What a great country we've got, or as you're told by your teachers, and that just wasn't so.
And you saw the extent to which the government would go to try and suppress opinions that were not in line with what the government wanted to hear decisively articulate.
Along that line, Nixon had his speech, November 3, 1969, to attack the Trump 42nd.
Do you hear that speech?
Yes.
said that the enemy was at home, and he was making accusations against all the students, especially the students, and their protests and stuff.
How did you feel about that when he said that?
That made me even more angry, because I was doing what I considered my right as an American, which was to express my opinion, speak out, exercise my free speech.
And there was a president saying,
You don't have the right to do that, or I don't want you doing that, because that speech doesn't agree with what I think your opinion ought to be.
And that was the very kind of attitude that I can only remember being told was the communist countries, where they wouldn't let you speak out.
You had to always speak in favor of the government, or whatever government line was being hoisted at that point.
So that was very upsetting.
How did you feel then about the silent majority and all the others that conformed to the government?
What were your thoughts?
feelings towards those people?

Well, my feelings were one of basically anger and frustration that people would allow themselves to be cowed into a way of thinking just because the president or the government was telling them, this is the way you should think.
This is the patriotic approach.
And if you're a patriot, you will do this.
It was this blind obedience to a line of policy that people were not questioning.
And that was upsetting.
I thought the greatest thing about this country was that you could question, you could speak out.
And that people would, if they had some questions, or would challenge the government.
But here, people were unwilling to do this.
There was a real climate of fear.
People were afraid about jobs, about if they spoke out, if they were perceived as dissidents.
And I think that was particularly so in 65, 66, and so on.
Do you think this was a result of the
the silent generation in the 50s and the conformity during that period and the anti-communism campaign.

Yeah, I think Nixon effectively tried to, and LBJ also, to evoke memories of McCarthy when we were trying to keep the commies out, that people who disagreed with the government policy were communists, that you could not be a patriot and disagree with government policy.
I mean, that was what they tried to promulgate as basically
an ideology that if you were a patriot, if you loved this country, you had to support whatever the government did.
And that was very frightening, because there were a lot of people who fought that.
And in many parts of this country at that point, you were a communist, you were guilty of treason if you spoke out against the Vietnam War.
Do you think the results of the war would have been different?
Say the war was in 59, intense in 59 instead of 69, and looking at the people of that era, do you think that the protests would have been strong, or do you think there might not have even been any?
It would have been very weak protests.
I mean, you probably had some protests on campuses in some of the major cities, but very, very few.
Yeah, I think at that point there would have been very little opposition.
What was it that made the 60s, in your opinion, what made them different from the kids in the 50s?
Well, I think this unwillingness to just accept things, a feeling that you just can't blindly obey what the government has to tell you.
You can't just accept things.
There's a feeling that you can change things, you can make things better.
I think a lot of us do very literally.
Can we say, yes, now what the country can do for you or what you can do for your country?
And part of it, I think, we felt was that if the government's policy is wrong or it's not what we believe to be correct, we've got a right to speak out.
In fact, we do need to speak out.
And I think that was more of what people in the 60s felt.
You don't just accept it.
Where, deep down, do you think that ideology comes from?
Is it strictly from what Kennedy said?
Was it because of upbringing?
Not so much.
High school education?
I think perhaps education.

I think it was more having education, both high school and college, where you, I think, professors perhaps had some, particularly in the more difficult universities, this idea of questioning authority.
And I think that's probably most with it.
You think it also?
because of the intensity of McCarthy and his campaigns.
And since that had died out, do you think that some of the braver students were willing to speak out?
